to take a public transportation to Ilidža. This is a city and neighborhood in Sarajevo Municipality in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bosnia and Herzegovina. It is a suburb of Sarajevo with a former industrial character, now predominantly residential. It is set only half a kilometer above sea level, so that its terrain resembles a mountain river basin, and it is bounded by a mountain range on the west and south - Velika bjelasnica on the top left corner of the map.

It looks just green and completely different from the city. I never realised that the lifestyle in Bosnia and Herzegovina is different from the life in Philippines. Even in this countryside, it feels exotic to me. The green environment makes me thirsty for their cold rivers and endless greens of plants. I can see their lifestyle includes less technology, more fresh air and green surroundings. Still we can see urban lifestyle; people going to Nokia museum, drinking fountains like the one in Sri Lanka.

Most city's around the world, I believe, you can find public transportations. You can take them to wherever you want, based on your destination or pre-determined route schedule. It is so different in my hometown, Philippines. Public transportations for me is next to impossible and no options here. You cannot take public transportations if you have to go somewhere.
